title: For Sale:  Randall 1911 45 acp Model c Raider A231.  1 of 574 made.
postcontent:
PLEASE NOTE, THE SERIAL NUMBER IS BLOCKED FOR PRIVACY ISSUES. IT HAS NOT BEEN ALTERED EXCEPT FOR THE PICTURE.  It is time for me to pass on the joy of owning this treasure. I have enjoyed shooting it for about 100 rounds and it has never failed. Ball and hollow point smooth and accurate. Please see the pictures and feel free to ask any questions. I will require face to face Florida DL and prefer CCW. I also will ship from my FFL to yours for actual cost. This is a rare and exceptionally well cared for, but not perfect Randall Service Model C / Raider with 2 Randall mags. The photo's do not show the true image of this pistol, it is much better in person. All parts are apparently original and function, will need recoil and firing pin springs in near future. There is not an idiot mark for the take down lever! How often is that possible?

RANDALL “COMMANDER”-SIZE .45 ACP PISTOLS
By August of 1983, Randall expanded its line of pistols to include the Service Model-C configuration. The “C” stood for compact. Initially, these handguns were even roll-marked “Service Model-C.” However, in the beginning of 1984, the company decided to give the guns a new identity, and dubbed this configuration as the “Raider,” so-named for General Randall’s unit which had been known as Randall’s Raiders.
Introduced August 31, 1983, the first in the Service Model-C series was the A211, which featured a round-top slide and fixed sights. Barrel length was 4.25-inches, making the over-all length .75-inch less than the standard A111. Magazine capacity (7) and height remained the same. Weight of the A211 was 36 ounces, compared to 38 ounces for the full-sized Model A111. After 992 of the Model A211 pistols were made, production of that model ceased on September 6, 1984. The serial number range went from RF02001C through RF05808C.
Next came the Model A231, which differed from the A211 in that it had a flat top slide and Millett Model 100 Gold Cup-type adjustable rear sight. The Model A231 was introduced on November 7, 1983. Only 574 of these pistols were manufactured, with a serial number range of RF02009C through RF03814C. The last of this model was manufactured on October 6, 1984.

title: For Sale:  Ruger LCP - .380 Amazing Condition + Upgrades + Extras
postcontent:
I am selling a Ruger .380 LCP. It can be considered a subcompact/Micro Compact carry weapon. Shoots very smoothly and has been taken care of. 

I purchased an amazing DeSantis Leather Wallet Holster that slides into the back pocket of shorts/pants easily. As seen in pictures, it is a tad bigger than a normal size wallet and appears to be a wallet when you are carrying concealed. 

Upgrades/Extras: 
I have upgraded the Guide-Rod and Spring. The original worked well (which is included) but I wanted to make sure that I never had feed issues and that it would feed/eject very smoothly for any ammo that I choose to put through there. I never had a single issue. 

Also includes a BlackHawk ankle holster (good for an extra conceal carry during winter). Works well but i prefer the wallet holster.

Includes a wide array of butt-plates for the 2 magazines. There are a couple extended finger buttplates that I purchased for when I go to the range and don't want to shoot with the wallet holster. It allows an extra finger on the gun for better control.

Also including a couple boxes of ammo. The 1st box is high end personal defense Speer Gold-Dot 90gr HP. Unused box and includes 20 rounds. Typically a good bit expensive compared to most other HP ammo. Also included is some old school Federal target ammo. x38 rounds are left. Shoot a little dirty but work great for target practice. Also included is x7 rounds of Hornady 90gr Critical Defense HP. I shot the other ones, but this x7 is what I typically carried in the magazine with me when concealed carry.

Condition:
It's in great condition. It's a 2-3yrs old so unfortunately it isn't the brand new one that came out but it is priced accordingly. Functions smoothly and flawlessly for me. The new upgraded (not a cheap knockoff) guide-rod/spring make shooting the gun even better. The original parts are included as well. Not a lot of rounds have been put through the gun. I've maybe put around 5-7 magazines (6 rounds each) through the gun since I purchased it. I usually shoot my 9mm. I am going to try something a little different which is the reason for selling.

Meeting: I will meet close to the Lexington area. I live right at the Junction of I-20/378 (Sunset BLVD) in Lexington. 4295 Sunset Blvd, Lexington, SC 29072 is probably the best and closet address that you can use if you want to look up directions.

Trades: Not looking for trades at the moment unless you have a long slide glock G34/G35/G17L/G24 or a G17 (FDE preferred) or a Long Slide FN 9/40. The Glock 19/17 are the only 2 guns that I would consider as a trade for a normal length slide.
**Yes, I know those are only partial trades and I would need to include cash.


Pricing: Currently it appears that the Ruger LCP is going for around 325+tax @PSA, and around 300 on GunBroker. That is for the basic weapon. I would like to get at least $275 firm for everything that I am including (holster/ammo/ankle holster/upgrades/butt plates). Original box/paperwork is included! For this price, please do not expect me to drive 20 miles out of my way. I try to be extremely forgiving when I sell firearms so I don't have to haggle with pricing so please be mindful. Thank you!

***SCDL or SC Concealed Carry Permit is REQUIRED*** - Responding to this ad leads me to believe that you are legally allowed to purchase said firearm and are of legal age requirements for SC.

title: For Sale:  Colt Lightweight Sporter AR15 Receiver - Retro
postcontent:
Here is an unusual item. This is a Colt AR15 Lightweight Sporter lower receiver, which has been modified for use in an M16A1 retro build, and has had one significant repair. Neither the mods nor the repair impact function. I have had this receiver installed on a rifle at the range and it functions perfectly. Sear block trigger, trigger guard (installed), and front pivot pin bushing adapters are included in the sale. The Modifications: This is an earlier Colt Lightweight Sporter receiver, originally manufactured with the large .315" front pivot pin hole for the two piece screw pin instead of the milspec .25" front pivot pin hole; the larger .170" "big pin" fire control pins instead of the standard milspec .155" pins; an integral sear block requiring use of a special sear block compatible trigger and half-moon style bolt carrier; and the SP1-style "slabside" configuration. This receiver has had several modifications, some reversible and some not. Permanent modifications: A) The fire control pin holes have been welded shut and re-drilled to the milspec standard .155" size using an 80% jig to accept milspec parts; and B) the upper projecting "horn" on the sear block has been removed to allow use of a standard full circle bolt carrier (note, however, that the sear block remains in place and fully functional, and still requires the special sear block trigger, included in the sale). Reversible modifications: A) An M16A1 style full fence, cannibalized from an 80% receiver, has been affixed using an epoxy adhesive. It is firmly attached and functional, but could presumably be removed. B) The two tabs above the selector found on milspec receivers have been added, also cannibalized from an 80% receiver and attached with an epoxy adhesive, and also presumably removable. C) Adapter bushings to convert the larger front pivot pin hole to the milspec .25" are included. One is affixed to the rifle by epoxy adhesive and could presumably be removed, the other is loose. D) the entire receiver has been coated using Brownell's Alumahyde II. This can be removed and the receiver refinished if desired (see comments on the forum boards on how to do that). The repair: A previous owner broke off one of the trigger guard ears. That missing part has been replaced with an ear cannibalized from an 80% receiver, which was drilled, tapped, and pinned in place. The repair is visible in the pictures. In order to avoid compromising the repair, I have left the trigger guard and roll pin in place and include it with the sale. Again, the sear block trigger, pivot pin adapter bushings, and installed trigger guard are included in the sale. 

E-MAIL for more pictures.
